#### Letting Flutter handle `Future`s with `FutureBuilder`
###### Now working with flutter example project geo_locate_pt2
In the scenario of retrieving some data asynchronously and updating the user interface..There is a widget for this case. Enter `FutureBuilder`. It automatically updates content when the `Future` arrives (LOL). `FutureBuilder` build itself based off the status of said `Future` allowing the `setState` instruction to be skipped. this programming pattern is called _reactive_ as it is a way for the UI to react to the data in a `Future`.
Consider the snippet below,
```dart 
body: Center(
	child: FutureBuilder(
	  future: position,
	  builder: (BuildContext context, AsyncSnapshot<Position> snapshot) {
		if (snapshot.connectionState == ConnectionState.waiting) {
		  return const CircularProgressIndicator();
		} else if (snapshot.connectionState == ConnectionState.done) {
		  if (snapshot.hasError) {
			return const Text('Something terrible happened!');
		  }
		  return Text(snapshot.data.toString());
		} else {
		  return const Text('');
		}
	  },
```
From the above we can infer the `Future` is a variable called `position`. This variable is initialized at the top of the class with `Future<Position>? position;`.  The declaration of this variable  occurs in the `initState()` with a call to `getPosition()`. See below,
```dart
  @override
  void initState() {
    super.initState();
    position = getPosition();
  }
```
The `FutureBuilder`s `builder` property is given an anonymous function with parameters `BuildContext` and `AsyncSnapshot<T>` where `T` is said `Future`.  Checking the status of the of the `AsyncSnapshot`is done with its `connectionState` property and comparing it with the `enum` `ConnectionState`. 
